{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17492434","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17492434"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:30:20+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:30:20+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1064"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1064","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1064"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.29,0.26,0.21,0.22,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1064"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69129"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1064","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1064"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1064"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54586"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"6"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"526"},{"type":"tags","id":"934"},{"type":"tags","id":"1109"},{"type":"tags","id":"1110"},{"type":"tags","id":"8753"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"735"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11430"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16938"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69129","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/69129"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 82-year-old woman presents to the surgical ward with increasing abdominal distension and absolute constipation four days after a laminectomy. Her medical history includes hypertension and an abdominal hysterectomy. Her regular medications include amlodipine and perindopril.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears uncomfortable. Her pulse rate is 100/min, blood pressure 140/90 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. Her abdomen is distended but soft with scant bowel sounds. Digital rectal examination reveals an empty rectum. An abdominal X-ray is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Sigmoid volvulus","Pseudo-obstruction","Paralytic ileus","Caecal volvulus","Small bowel volvulus"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe abdominal X-ray demonstrates dilated loops of large bowel with a markedly distended caecum, without evidence of mechanical obstruction. This pattern, occurring in the post-operative setting, is characteristic of acute colonic pseudo-obstruction (Ogilvie syndrome).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPseudo-obstruction\u003C/strong\u003E is defined as severe colonic distension without mechanical obstruction. It typically occurs in elderly patients following surgery, trauma, or severe illness. The pathophysiology involves autonomic dysfunction leading to decreased colonic motility. The key concern is caecal distension beyond 9 cm, which significantly increases perforation risk.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESigmoid volvulus\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with a \u0027coffee bean\u0027 appearance on X-ray, with a dilated loop of bowel arising from the pelvis. The characteristic \u0027bird\u0027s beak\u0027 sign would be visible at the point of twist. These features are absent here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EParalytic ileus\u003C/strong\u003E primarily affects the small bowel rather than the colon and would show dilated small bowel loops with multiple air-fluid levels. While it can occur post-operatively, the pattern of colonic involvement here is more consistent with pseudo-obstruction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECaecal volvulus\u003C/strong\u003E presents with a dilated caecum that is typically displaced to the left upper quadrant, often with a \u0027bird\u0027s beak\u0027 appearance at the point of torsion. The remaining colon would not show the generalised dilatation seen here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESmall bowel volvulus\u003C/strong\u003E would present with dilated small bowel loops and multiple air-fluid levels, not the colonic dilatation pattern seen in this image.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EManagement of pseudo-obstruction includes cessation of opioids, correction of electrolyte abnormalities, and close monitoring of caecal diameter. Decompression via colonoscopy or neostigmine are additional options for those not improving with conservative management\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Pseudo-obstruction (Ogilvie syndrome) presents with colonic distension without mechanical obstruction, typically following surgery or severe illness.","The caecal diameter must be monitored closely as perforation risk increases significantly when \u003E9 cm.","Key radiological features include progressive colonic dilatation with relative sparing of the rectosigmoid."],"references":["Wells CI, O\u0027Grady G, Bissett IP. Acute colonic pseudo-obstruction: A systematic review of aetiology and mechanisms. World J Gastroenterol 2017;23:5634-44. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28852322/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54586"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1064"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18398"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18398","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18398"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/27b63c64-97e6-4faa-90dc-90f205693a7a.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storag